snippet.textDisplay: @Photoandcargeek I completely understand it, but until now the GT3’s typically have NOT been sold at a massive markup, neither new nor slightly used. That unfortunate trend seems to have only become an issue over the past 7/8 years or so. Porsche frowns upon its dealers marking their cars up to the insanely high prices that other brands dealers do (like $150k+ for $75k C8, $130k+ for a $50/$60k Bronco or $270k for a $110/$115k new HUMMER EV). It’s just odd hearing all these supposed horror stories from folks when I’ve walked into two different Porsche dealerships in two different states and ordered two separate cars from people & dealers I’ve never dealt with before - one of which was a GT3. The other was a 991.2 Targa 4 GTS AND I’ve already spec’ed a GT4 RS that I’m currently waiting on to be delivered. I’m not the only member of my family or person I’m aware of that’s done this either.

snippet.textDisplay: @Kyusha Coming from a family packed full of both auto enthusiasts and Porsche fanatics AND the fact that I actually DO have an IQ over 50 I’m very well aware of what the car is, but thanks for reiterating what we all saw in this very video Caption Obvious. But saying just because it IS a limited edition vehicle that enthusiasts won’t buy it is one of the most (if not THE most) ridiculous bunch of nonsense I’ve ever heard. 911R’s, Speedsters and even the most recent 911 Targa 4S Heritage Edition have *ALL* been purchased by enthusiasts. Saying they won’t is just as equally asinine as saying someone isn’t a true enthusiast if they don’t work on their own cars — which, just for the record, is probably one of THE stupidest things I’ve ever heard uttered.

snippet.textDisplay: @Photoandcargeek Why the hell have you “been trying to buy” one for 12 years? There’s this nifty tiny little segment out there know as the USED car market. So instead of being Mr Sensitive and getting all butthurt over what a dealer supposedly said to you, why - if you TRULY wanted a GT3 that badly - would you not explore ALL of your options? snippet.textDisplay: @Pineapple Tacos I wish that what you’ve described here was actually the case at the moment. Unfortunately, just about everything on PORSCHE dealer lots are going for well over msrp (aside from run of the mill Macans and Cayennes). Was at my local dealer a couple of weeks ago and saw $50k markups on both a 992 911 GTS and Taycan Sport Turismo GTS. At the time, even placing a deposit in the hope of securing an allocation for a 992 GTS required agreement to purchase at $25k over sticker. #1 on that list for allocation agreed to $80k over sticker. Since then, they’ve actually declined any deposits for “sports cars due the uncertainty around future delivery times”. Likely different scenarios depending on various markets and dealerships but not a good time for a normal guy like me to be trying to secure an allocation for anything (plus, out of principal, I’m not willing to pay over sticker).
